{
  "answer": "**Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1.**\n\nThe work compares judicial inquiry into the truth via circumstantial evidence to tracking a wounded animal, quoting verbatim:\n\n> Just as a hunter tracks a wounded deer by the trail of blood in the thicket, so should one trace the path of justice by its clues.[^1]\n\nThis passage occurs in a discussion of legal procedure, akin to the Arthaśāstra, emphasizing how a judge (or authority) discerns justice from indirect signs.[^1]: /works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-21ca46",
